# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bill-hill-baseball
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bill-hill-baseball/1896-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1896 throughout the world.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/1896-in-baseball] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/1897-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1897 throughout the world.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/1898-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1898 throughout the world.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/1899-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1899 throughout the world.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/1899-in-baseball] Buck Freeman of the Washington Senators leads all batters with 25 home runs during the regular season, more than double hit by Bobby Wallace of the St.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/1899-in-baseball] Louis Perfectos, who finished with 12 homers.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/1899-in-baseball] Freeman's tally was not surpassed until 1919, when Babe Ruth belted 29 home runs for the Boston Red Sox.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/1899-in-baseball] The National League would remain at eight teams until 1962.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] The **Baltimore Orioles** were a 19th-century professional baseball team that competed from 1882 to 1899, first in the American Association and later in the National League.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] Despite their success, the dominant Orioles were contracted out of the National League after the 1899 season, when the league reduced in size from 12 members to eight.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] Most of the Orioles' best players moved to the Brooklyn Superbas—Baltimore owner Harry Von der Horst also had an ownership stake in Brooklyn.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] Upon the foundation of the American League in 1901, a reorganized Baltimore Orioles franchise competed as a charter member for two seasons, before folding and being replaced by the New York Highlanders, later renamed the New York Yankees.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] The team, formally the "Baltimore Base Ball and Exhibition Company", was founded in 1882 as a charter member of the American Association (AA), considered a major league.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] The Orioles finished last in the league in four of their first five season, the exception being a sixth-place finish in 1884 when 13 different teams played in the league.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] The team then had its best positional finish, third place, in 1887, followed by two seasons finishing fifth in the then eight-team league.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] The Orioles dropped out of the league after the 1889 season, and began the 1890 season playing in the minor-league Atlantic Association.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] However, when the last-place Brooklyn Gladiators of the AA folded in late August, the Orioles re-joined the AA and played 38 games to complete the 1890 season, posting a record of 15–19 with four ties.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] The Orioles remained in the AA for 1891, finishing sixth among nine teams in the AA's final season.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] Overall, during 10 seasons of AA play, the Orioles had a cumulative record of 489–602 (.448).
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] The Orioles were one of four AA clubs (the others being the Louisville Colonels, St.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] Louis Browns, and Washington Statesmen) merged into the National League (NL) in 1892, formally as a 12-member "League Association".
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] The beginnings of the team can be traced to June 1892, when owner Harry Von der Horst hired Ned Hanlon to be manager of the Orioles, giving him stock in the team and full authority over baseball operations.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] Hanlon moved his growing family to a house that stood a block away from the team's ballpark.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] After finishing last in the league in 1892 and eighth in 1893, the Orioles won three consecutive pennants during 1894–1896, featuring several future Hall of Famers under manager Hanlon.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] They followed up the title run with two second-place finishes, in 1897 and 1898.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] Accordingly, they participated in all four editions of the post-season Temple Cup series, held from 1894 through 1897 between the NL's top two teams, winning in 1896 and 1897.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] After the team's 1898 second-place finish, most of the team's stars were moved to the Brooklyn Bridegrooms, who were renamed as the Superbas for 1899 and eventually became known as the Dodgers.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] The players moved when Von der Horst and Hanlon became part owners of the Brooklyn team, with Hanlon also becoming Brooklyn's manager.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] Third baseman John McGraw and catcher Wilbert Robinson remained in Baltimore, with McGraw remaining as first-year player-manager.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] Following a fourth-place finish in 1899, the Orioles were one of four clubs eliminated by the NL (the others being the Cleveland Spiders, Louisville Colonels, and the aforementioned Washington Statesmen, then known as the Washington Senators).
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] During their eight seasons of play in the NL, the Orioles compiled an overall record of 644–447 (.590).
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] In the eight-team NL of 1900, McGraw and Robinson joined the St.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] In 1901, McGraw followed through on his threats to abandon the NL and form a club in the rival American League (AL), being formed by new president Ban Johnson out of the former minor-league Western League.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] These newly formed Orioles of the AL only stayed in Baltimore for two seasons.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] In 1903, a team was established in New York City as "the price of peace" as agreement between the older circuit (the NL) and its new upstart rival (the AL) allowing the "Americans" to have a team based in the city as a sign of respectability.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] The AL team in New York became known as the New York Highlanders (or occasionally the New York Americans), later renamed in 1913 as the New York Yankees.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] The Yankees do not consider the 1901–1902 Baltimore team as part of their history.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] In 1903, an Orioles franchise in the old minor-league Eastern League filled the void left by the departure of the major-league Orioles.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] These minor-league Orioles included local product and future baseball icon Babe Ruth and Lefty Grove.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] The team won a string of seven straight titles, 1919–1925, at the then highest level of the minor leagues in the reorganized International League (known as such from 1912 onward).
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] A major-league franchise did not return to Baltimore until the St.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] Louis Browns (not the Browns of the AA, but a team that had its origins in Milwaukee) relocated to the city in 1954 and was renamed as the current Baltimore Orioles of Major League Baseball.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] The Orioles of the American Association first played at Newington Park for the 1882 season.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] Starting in 1883, the team played at the old Oriole Park, in Harwood, south of the Waverly neighborhood at 29th and Barclay Streets, just a block west from Greenmount Avenue, remaining there into the 1891 season.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] The 1901–1902 American League team played at Oriole Park a decade later.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] During the 1891 season, the Orioles moved a few blocks away to Union Park on Huntington Avenue (later renamed 25th Street) and Greenmount Avenue.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] The team remained at Union Park for its entire time in the National League, 1892 through 1899.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] The original Orioles were one of the most storied teams in the history of the game.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] Managed by Ned Hanlon, they won NL pennants in 1894, 1895, and 1896, and sported some of the most colorful players in history including John McGraw, Wee Willie Keeler, Hughie Jennings, Joe Kelley, Wilbert Robinson, and Dan Brouthers.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] They were rough characters who practically invented "scientific" baseball, the form of baseball played before the home run became the norm in the 1920s.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] Like the style known today as "small ball", the "inside baseball" strategy of Orioles featured tight pitching, hit and run tactics, stolen bases, and precise bunting.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] One such play, where the batter deliberately strikes the pitched ball downward onto the infield surface with sufficient force such that the ball rebounds skyward, allowing the batter to reach first base safely before the opposing team can field the ball, remains known as a Baltimore chop.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baltimore-orioles-19th-century] Matt Kilroy pitched a no-hitter for the Orioles on October 6, 1886; Bill Hawke threw one on August 16, 1893, the first from the modern pitching distance of 60 feet, 6 inches; and Jay Hughes threw a no-hitter for the Orioles on April 22, 1898.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baseball-reference] Founder Sean Forman began developing the website while working on his Ph.D. dissertation in applied math and computational science at the University of Iowa.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baseball-reference] While writing his dissertation, he had also been writing articles on and blogging about sabermetrics.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baseball-reference] Forman's database was originally built from the *Total Baseball* series of baseball encyclopedias.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baseball-reference] The website went online in April 2000, after first being launched in February 2000 as part of the website for the *Big Bad Baseball Annual*.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baseball-reference] It was originally built as a web interface to the Lahman Baseball Database, though it now employs a variety of data sources.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baseball-reference] In 2004, Forman founded Sports Reference.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baseball-reference] Sports Reference is a website that came out of the Baseball Reference website.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baseball-reference] The company was incorporated as Sports Reference, LLC in 2007.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baseball-reference] In 2006, Forman left his job as a math professor at Saint Joseph's University to focus on Baseball Reference full-time.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baseball-reference] In February 2009, Fantasy Sports Ventures took a minority stake in Sports Reference, for a "low seven-figure sum".
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baseball-reference] In late April 2021, the site changed a number of identifying names, "discontinuing the use of nicknames that are racially or ethnically influenced" and "names based upon a player's disability", such as Chief Bender and Dummy Hoy, who are now listed as Charles Bender and Billy Hoy, respectively.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baseball-reference] To compare ballplayers to one-another it offers "Black Ink" and "Gray Ink" tests, which tally a player's dominance and overall productivity against his peers.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baseball-reference] In 2012, it began to offer Jay Jaffe's Jaffe Wins Above Replacement Score (JAWS) statistic for comparing players of different eras against each other by weighing their performance in the prime as well as their entire career.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baseball-reference] Baseball Reference began including its version of Wins Above Replacement (WAR) in 2010.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baseball-reference] Its version determining a player's value differs slightly from other baseball statistics websites, including FanGraphs and Baseball Prospectus.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baseball-reference] Baseball Reference has its own baseball encyclopedia, a wiki called "Baseball Reference Bullpen", which can be edited by anyone and is modeled after Wikipedia.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/baseball-reference] As of November 2025, the Bullpen contains more than 123,000 articles.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/bill-hill-baseball] Born in Chattanooga, Tennessee, Hill died in Cincinnati at the age of 63 and was interred at Evergreen Cemetery in the Cincinnati suburb of Southgate, Kentucky.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/bill-hill-baseball] His younger brother, Hugh Hill, was a Major League outfielder who played during the 1903 and 1904 seasons.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The **Brooklyn Dodgers** were a Major League Baseball team founded in 1883 as the **Brooklyn Grays**.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] In 1884, it became a member of the American Association as the **Brooklyn Atlantics** before joining the National League in 1890.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] They remained in Brooklyn, New York, until 1957, after which the team moved to Los Angeles, where it continues its history as the Los Angeles Dodgers.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] That same year, the Dodgers' longtime rival, the New York Giants, moved to San Francisco and became the San Francisco Giants.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The "Dodgers" team name is a shortened form of one of their former names, the **Brooklyn Trolley Dodgers.** "Trolley dodgers" is a nickname for Brooklyn residents who had to avoid being hit by the city's fast-moving trolleys while crossing their lines.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The Dodgers later earned the respectful nickname **Dem Bums**.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The Dodgers played in two stadiums in South Brooklyn, each named Washington Park, and at Eastern Park in the neighborhood of Brownsville before moving to Ebbets Field in the neighborhood of Crown Heights in 1912.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The team is noted for signing Jackie Robinson in 1947 as the first black player in the modern major leagues.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The Brooklyn Dodgers had an overall win–loss record of 5,624–5,290–133 (.515) during their 68 years in Brooklyn.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Eight former Brooklyn Dodgers players were elected to the National Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Many of the clubs represented at the first convention of the National Association of Base Ball Players (NABBP) were from Brooklyn, including the Atlantic, Eckford, and Excelsior clubs that combined to dominate play for most of the 1860s.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Brooklyn helped make baseball commercial, as the locale of the first paid admission games, a series of three all star contests matching New York and Brooklyn in 1858.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Brooklyn also featured the first two enclosed baseball grounds, the Union Grounds and the Capitoline Grounds; enclosed, dedicated ballparks accelerated the evolution from amateurism to professionalism.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Despite the early success of Brooklyn clubs in the NABBP, which were officially amateur until 1869, they fielded weak teams in the succeeding National Association of Professional Base Ball Players (NAPBBP), the first professional league formed in 1871.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The Excelsiors no longer challenged for the amateur championship after the Civil War (1861–1865) and never entered the professional NAPBBP (aka NA).
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The Eckfords and Atlantics declined to join until 1872 and thereby lost their best players; the Eckfords survived only one season and the Atlantics four, with losing teams.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The National League (NL) replaced the NAPBBP in 1876 and granted exclusive territories to its eight members, excluding the Atlantics in favor of the Mutual Club of New York who had shared home grounds with the Atlantics.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] When the Mutuals were expelled by the league, the Hartford club moved in, the press dubbing them the **Brooklyn Hartfords**, and played its home games at Union Grounds in 1877 before disbanding.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The team currently known as the Dodgers was formed in 1883 by real estate magnate and baseball enthusiast Charles Byrne, who convinced his brother-in-law Joseph Doyle and casino operator Ferdinand Abell to start the team with him.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Byrne arranged to build a grandstand on a lot bounded by Third Street, Fourth Avenue, Fifth Street, and Fifth Avenue, and named it Washington Park in honor of first president George Washington.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Nicknamed by reporters the **"Grays"** for their uniforms, the team played in the minor league Inter-State Association of Professional Baseball Clubs that first season.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Doyle became the first team manager, and they drew 6,431 fans to their first home game on May 12, 1883, against the Trenton, New Jersey team.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The Grays won the league title after the Camden Merritt club in New Jersey disbanded on July 20 and Brooklyn picked up some of its better players.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The Grays were invited to join the two-year-old professional circuit, the American Association (founded 1882) to compete with the eight-year-old NL for the 1884 season.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] They lost the 1889 championship tournament to the New York Giants and tied the 1890 championship with Louisville.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Their success during this period was partly attributed to their having absorbed skilled players from the defunct AA New York Metropolitans and one-year Players' League entry the Brooklyn Ward's Wonders.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The middle years of the decade were disappointing, a slump the Spalding Guide rather primly ascribed to management tolerating drunkenness among the players.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Over the 1890s, Charles Ebbets accumulated shares in the club, owning 80% of it by decade's end.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Other shares were held by Harry Von der Horst, owner of the Baltimore Orioles team that won consecutive championships in 1894, 1895, and 1896, and Orioles manager Ned Hanlon.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] In 1899, Von der Horst and Hanlon moved most of the Orioles' stars from Baltimore to join the Grays (Bridegrooms) in Brooklyn; Hanlon became the team's manager.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The press, inspired by the popular circus act The Hanlons' Superba, dubbed the new combined team the **Brooklyn Superbas**.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] In 1899 and in 1900, they were the champions of the National League.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The name Brooklyn Trolley Dodgers was first used to describe the team in 1895.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Some sources erroneously report that the name "Trolley Dodgers" referred to pedestrians avoiding fast cars on street car tracks that bordered Eastern Park on two sides.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] However, Eastern Park was not bordered by street-level trolley lines that had to be "dodged" by pedestrians.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The name "Trolley Dodgers" implied the dangers posed by trolley cars in Brooklyn generally, which in 1892, began the switch from horse-power to electrical power, which made them much faster, and were hence regarded as more dangerous.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The name was later shortened to **Brooklyn Dodgers**.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] All of these nicknames were used by fans and newspaper sportswriters to describe the team, often concurrently, but not in any official capacity.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The team's legal name was the **Brooklyn Base Ball Club**.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The "Trolley Dodgers" nickname was used throughout this period, along with other nicknames, by fans and sports writers of the day.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The team did not use the name in a formal sense until 1916, when the name was printed on home World Series programs.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The word "Dodgers" appeared on team jerseys in 1932.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The "conclusive shift" came in 1933, when both home and road jerseys for the team bore the name "Dodgers".
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Examples of how the many popularized names of the team were used interchangeably are available from newspaper articles from the period before 1932.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Most baseball statistics sites and baseball historians generally now refer to the pennant-winning 1916 Brooklyn team as the Robins; on the other hand, the *Brooklyn Daily Eagle* used "Superbas" in its box scores that season.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] A 1918 *New York Times* article used the nickname Robins in its title "Buccaneers Take Last From Robins", but the subtitle of the article reads "Subdue The Superbas By 11 To 4, Making Series An Even Break".
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Space-conscious headline writers still used "the Flock" (derived from "Robins") during the Dodgers' last decade in Brooklyn.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Another example of the interchangeability of different nicknames is found on the program issued at Ebbets Field for the 1920 World Series, which identifies the matchup in the series as "Dodgers vs.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Indians", despite the fact that the Robins nickname had been in consistent usage at this point for around six years.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] For most of the first half of the 20th century, no Major League Baseball team employed a black player.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] A parallel system of Negro leagues developed, but most Negro league players were denied a chance to prove their skill before a wider national audience.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Jackie Robinson became the first African-American to play in MLB in the 20th century when he played his first NL game on April 15, 1947 for the Dodgers.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Robinson's entry into the league was mainly due to general manager Branch Rickey's efforts.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The deeply religious Rickey's motivation appears to have been primarily moral, although business considerations were also present.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Rickey was a member of the Methodist Church, the antecedent denomination to the United Methodist Church of today, which was a strong advocate for social justice and active later in the Civil Rights Movement.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Rickey saw his opportunity with the 1944 death of Commissioner Kenesaw Mountain Landis, an arch-segregationist and enforcer of the color barrier.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Besides selecting Robinson for his exceptional baseball skills, Rickey also considered Robinson's outstanding personal character, his UCLA education and rank of captain in the U.S.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Army in his decision, since he knew that boos, taunts, and criticism were going to be directed at Robinson, and that Robinson had to be tough enough to withstand abuse without attempting to retaliate.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The inclusion of Robinson on the team also led the Dodgers to move its spring training site.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Prior to 1946, the Dodgers held their spring training in Jacksonville, Florida.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] However, the city's stadium refused to host an exhibition game with the Montreal Royals, the Dodgers' own farm club, on whose roster Robinson appeared at the time, citing segregation laws.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Ultimately, City Island Ballpark in Daytona Beach agreed to host the game with Robinson on the field.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The team traveled to Havana, Cuba for spring training in 1947, this time with Robinson on the big club.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Although the Dodgers ultimately built Dodgertown and its Holman Stadium further south in Vero Beach, and played there for 61 spring training seasons from 1948 through 2008, Daytona Beach renamed City Island Ballpark to Jackie Robinson Ballpark in his honor.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] This event marked the continuation of the integration of professional sports in the United States, with professional football having led the way in 1946, with the concomitant demise of the Negro leagues, and is regarded as a key moment in the history of the American civil rights movement.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Robinson was an exceptional player, a speedy runner who sparked the team with his intensity.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] He was the inaugural recipient of the Rookie of the Year award, which is now named the Jackie Robinson award in his honor.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The Dodgers' willingness to integrate, when most other teams refused to, was a key factor in their 1947–1956 success.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] They won six pennants in those 10 years with the help of Robinson, three-time MVP Roy Campanella, Cy Young Award winner Don Newcombe, Jim Gilliam, and Joe Black.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Robinson eventually became the first African-American elected to the Baseball Hall of Fame in 1962.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] After the wilderness years of the 1920s and 1930s, the Dodgers were rebuilt into a contending club first by general manager Larry MacPhail and then the legendary Branch Rickey.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The annual ritual of building excitement, followed in the end by disappointment, became a common pattern to the long suffering fans, and **"Wait 'til next year!"** became an unofficial Dodger slogan.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] While the Dodgers generally enjoyed success during this period, in 1951 they fell victim to one of the largest collapses in the history of baseball.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] On August 11, 1951, Brooklyn led the National League by an enormous 13+1⁄2 games over their archrivals, the Giants.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] While the Dodgers went 26–22 from that time until the end of the season, the Giants went on to win 37 of their last 44 games, including their last seven in a row.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] At the end of the season the Dodgers and the Giants were tied for first place, forcing a three-game playoff for the pennant.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The Giants took Game 1 by a score of 3–1 before being shut out by the Dodgers' Clem Labine in Game 2, 10–0.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Brooklyn held a 4–2 lead in the bottom of the ninth inning of Game 3.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Giants outfielder Bobby Thomson, however, hit a stunning three-run walk-off home run off the Dodgers' Ralph Branca to secure the NL Championship for the Giants.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Thomson's home run is known as the Shot Heard 'Round The World.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] In 1955, by which time the core of the Dodger team was beginning to age, "next year" finally came.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The fabled "Boys of Summer" shot down the "Bronx Bombers" in seven games, led by the first-class pitching of young left-hander Johnny Podres, whose key pitch was a changeup known as "pulling down the lampshade" because of the arm motion used right when the ball was released.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Podres won two Series games, including the deciding seventh.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The turning point of Game 7 was a spectacular double play that began with left fielder Sandy Amorós running down Yogi Berra's long fly ball, then throwing to shortstop Pee Wee Reese, who relayed to first baseman Gil Hodges to double up a surprised Gil McDougald to preserve the Dodger lead.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Hank Bauer grounded out and the Dodgers won 2–0.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Although the Dodgers lost the World Series to the Yankees in 1956, during which the Yankees pitcher Don Larsen pitched the only World Series perfect game in baseball history and the only post-season no-hitter for the next 54 years, it hardly seemed to matter.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Lawyer and real estate businessman Walter O'Malley had acquired majority ownership of the Dodgers in 1950, when he bought Rickey's 25 percent share of the team and secured the support of the widow of another equal partner, John L.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Soon O'Malley was working to buy new land in Brooklyn for a new, more accessible and better ballpark than Ebbets Field.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Beloved as it was, Ebbets Field had grown old and was not well served by vehicular infrastructure, to the point where the Dodgers could not "sell out" the park to maximum capacity even in the heat of a pennant race, despite dominating the league from 1946 to 1957.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] New York City Construction Coordinator Robert Moses sought to force O'Malley into using a site in Flushing Meadows, Queens – the eventual location of Shea Stadium (which opened in 1964), the home of the future New York Mets, who began play in 1962.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Moses' vision involved a city-built, city-owned park, which was greatly at odds with O'Malley's real-estate savvy.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] When O'Malley realized that he was not going to be allowed to buy a suitable parcel of land in Brooklyn, he began thinking of moving the team.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] O'Malley was free to purchase land of his own choosing but wanted Moses to condemn a parcel of land along the Atlantic Railroad Yards in downtown Brooklyn under Title I authority, after O'Malley had bought the bulk of the land he had in mind.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Title I gave the city power to condemn land for the purpose of building what it calls "public purpose" projects.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Moses' interpretation of "public purpose" included public parks, housing, highways, and bridges.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] What O'Malley wanted was for Moses to use Title I authority, rather than to pay market value for the land.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] With Title I the city via Robert Moses could have sold the land to O'Malley at a below market price.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Meanwhile, non-stop transcontinental airline travel had become routine during the years since World War II.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Teams were no longer bound by much slower railroad infrastructure.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Because of advances in civil aviation, it became possible to locate teams farther apart, as far west as California, while maintaining the same game schedules.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] When Los Angeles officials attended the 1956 World Series looking to entice a team to move there, they were not even thinking of the Dodgers.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Their original target had been the Washington Senators franchise, which eventually moved to Bloomington, Minnesota to become the Minnesota Twins in 1961.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] At the same time, O'Malley was looking for a contingency in case Moses and other New York politicians refused to let him build the Brooklyn stadium he wanted and sent word to the Los Angeles officials that he was interested in talking.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Los Angeles offered him what New York did not: a chance to buy land somewhat suitable for building a ballpark and the chance to own that ballpark, giving him complete control over all its revenue streams.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] At the same time, the National League was not willing to approve the Dodgers' move unless O'Malley found a second team willing to join them out west, largely out of concern for travel costs.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Meanwhile, Giants owner Horace Stoneham was having similar difficulty finding a replacement for his team's antiquated home stadium, the Polo Grounds.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Unlike O'Malley, Stoneham did not engage in a serious effort to identify a location for a replacement for the Polo Grounds.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Stoneham was considering moving the Giants to Minneapolis but was persuaded instead to move them to San Francisco, ensuring that the Dodgers had a National League rival closer than St.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] So, the two arch-rival teams, the Dodgers and Giants, moved out to the West Coast together after the 1957 season.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The Brooklyn Dodgers played their final game at Ebbets Field on September 24, 1957, which the Dodgers won 2–0 over the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] On April 18, 1958, the Los Angeles Dodgers played their first game in L.A., defeating the former New York and newly moved and renamed San Francisco Giants, 6–5, before 78,672 fans at the Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Catcher Roy Campanella, left partially paralyzed in an off-season automobile accident on January 28, 1958, never played for the Dodgers in Los Angeles.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] With the threat of a New York team joining the new Continental League, the National League expanded by adding the New York Mets following a proposal from William Shea.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] In a symbolic reference to New York's earlier National League teams, the new team took as its primary colors the blue of the Dodgers and the orange of the Giants, both of which are colors also featured on the flag of New York City.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The historic and heated rivalry between the Dodgers and the Giants is more than a century old.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] It began when the Dodgers and Giants faced each other in the 1889 World Series, the ancestor of the Subway Series, and both played in separate, neighboring cities.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Brooklyn and New York were separate cities until 1898, when they became neighboring boroughs of the newly consolidated New York City.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] When both franchises moved to California after the 1957 season, the rivalry was easily transplanted, as the cities of Los Angeles and San Francisco have long been economic, political, and cultural rivals, representative of the broader Southern/Northern California divide.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Manager Wilbert Robinson, another former Oriole, popularly known as "Uncle Robbie", restored the Brooklyn team to respectability.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] His "Brooklyn Robins" reached the 1916 and 1920 World Series, losing both, but contending perennially for several seasons.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Charles Ebbets and Ed McKeever died within a week of each other in 1925, and Robbie was named president while still field manager.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Upon assuming the title of president, however, Robinson's ability to focus on the field declined, and the teams of the late 1920s were often fondly referred to as the "Daffiness Boys" for their distracted, error-ridden style of play.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Outfielder Babe Herman was the leader both in hitting and in zaniness.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The signature Dodger play from this era occurred when three players, Dazzy Vance, Chick Fewster, and Herman, ended up at third base at the same time.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The play is often remembered as Herman "tripling into a triple play", though only two of the three players were declared out and Herman was credited with a double rather than a triple.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Herman later complained that no one remembered that he drove in the winning run on the play.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] After his removal as club president, Robinson returned to managing, and the club's performance rebounded somewhat.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] When Robinson retired in 1931, he was replaced as manager by Max Carey, who had played for the team from 1926 until 1929.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Although some suggested renaming the "Robins" the "Brooklyn Canaries", after Carey, whose last name was originally "Carnarius", the name "Brooklyn Dodgers" returned to stay following Robinson's retirement.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] It was during this era that Willard Mullin, a noted sports cartoonist, fixed the Brooklyn team with the lovable nickname of "Dem Bums".
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] After hearing his cab driver ask, "So how did those bums do today?", Mullin decided to sketch an exaggerated version of famed circus clown Emmett Kelly to represent the Dodgers in his much-praised cartoons in the *New York World-Telegram*.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Both image and nickname caught on, so much so that many a Dodger yearbook cover, from 1951 through 1957, featured a Willard Mullin illustration of the Brooklyn Bum.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Perhaps the highlight of the Daffiness Boys era came after Wilbert Robinson left the dugout.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] As it happened, the season entered its final games with the Giants tied with the St.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Louis Cardinals for the pennant, with the Giants' remaining games against the Dodgers.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Stengel led his Bums to the Polo Grounds for the showdown, and they beat the Giants twice to knock them out of the pennant race.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The "Gashouse Gang" Cardinals nailed the pennant by beating the Cincinnati Reds those same two days.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] One key development during this era was the 1938 appointment of Leland "Larry" MacPhail as Dodgers' general manager.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] MacPhail, who brought night games to Major League Baseball as general manager of the Reds, also started night baseball in Brooklyn and ordered the successful refurbishing of Ebbets Field.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] He also brought Reds voice Red Barber to Brooklyn as the Dodgers' lead announcer in 1939, just after MacPhail broke the New York baseball executives' agreement to ban live baseball broadcasts, enacted because of the fear of the effect of radio calls on the home teams' attendance.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] MacPhail remained with the Dodgers until 1942, when he returned to the Armed Forces for World War II.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] He later became one of the Yankees' co-owners, bidding unsuccessfully for Barber to join him in the Bronx as announcer.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The first major-league baseball game to be televised was Brooklyn's 6–1 victory over Cincinnati at Ebbets Field on August 26, 1939.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Batting helmets were introduced to Major League Baseball by the Dodgers in 1941.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The Dodgers met the Yankees, another New York team, seven times in the World Series, more than any other two teams from the American and National Leagues before 1958.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The Yankees are 6–1 against the Brooklyn Dodgers in the World Series, with the Dodgers winning their first and only World Series title against the Yankees, four games to three, in 1955.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] After the Dodgers moved to Los Angeles in 1958, the rivalry continued as the teams met five more times in the World Series and represented two of the largest cities on each coast of the United States.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Since 1958, the Dodgers have improved their record against the Yankees in the World Series; they are currently leading 3–2.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Fan support has added to the notoriety of the series as both teams are supported by two of the largest fanbases in North America.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Although the rivalry's significance arose from the two teams' numerous World Series meetings, the Yankees and Dodgers did not meet in the World Series between 1981 and 2024.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] They did not play each other again in a non-exhibition game until 2004, when they played a three-game interleague series.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Nevertheless, games between the two teams have drawn sellout crowds.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The Cardinals–Dodgers rivalry was particularly intense from 1941 through 1949.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] In 1942 the Cardinals overcame a 10 game Dodger lead in early August to win the pennant.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] In 1946 the Cardinals and Dodgers finished the regular season tied for first place but the Cardinals won the pennant when they prevailed in the first ever playoff tiebreaker in the National League.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] During this period, after the 1942 season, Branch Rickey, who had built up the Cardinals farm system as their general manager moved to become the Dodgers' general manager.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] In 1947, after Rickey broke the color line by signing Jackie Robinson to the Dodgers, there were rumors that southerners playing for the Cardinals were planning to boycott games against the Dodgers, although the players later denied it.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] In general, the Cardinals were latecomers to integration.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Front-office executive Bing Devine said the owner from 1947 to 1953, Fred Saigh, refused to sign black players.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Louis was, in many ways, a Southern city.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] In the mid-1950s many of its stores and restaurants refused to serve black customers.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The Cardinals, with baseball's largest radio network blanketing the Midwest and South, had cultivated white Southern fans.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Their ballpark was also the last in the majors to abolish segregated seating.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Because of their lack of black players, the Cardinals play suffered on the field tremendously in the 1950s.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Meanwhile, with the success of Robinson, the Dodgers doubled down on the opportunity to sign players of color from the Negro leagues.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] In the subsequent years after their pennant-winning season in 1947, they would sign Don Newcombe, Roy Campanella, and Jim Gilliam from the Negro leagues, adding to an already tremendous team.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The Dodgers made the World Series in 1949, 1952, 1953, 1955, and 1956 (winning championships in 1955) and were a historic pennant race away from making it in 1951, in part because they were the first to accept African American players.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The 1951 season included a 14-game winning streak for the Dodgers against the Cardinals, the longest such streak in the rivalry.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The Dodgers have retired seven numbers in the history of the franchise related to its tenure in Brooklyn.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The following are of those whose contributions to the Dodgers took place either entirely or significantly in Brooklyn.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] In 1997, 50 years after he broke the color barrier and 25 years after the Dodgers retired his number, Robinson's No.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] 42 was retired throughout Major League Baseball.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Robinson is the only major league baseball player so honored.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Starting in the 2007 season, Jackie Robinson Day (April 15, commemorating the Opening Day of Robinson's rookie season of 1947) has featured many or all players and coaches wearing the number 42 as a tribute to Robinson.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] In 2019, the Dodgers established "Legends of Dodger Baseball", which is meant to honor Dodger greats whose numbers have not been retired.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] The program honors those who made an "impact on the franchise, both on and off the field." Recipients are recognized with plaques at Dodger Stadium.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] Of these players, only one was primarily a Brooklyn Dodgers.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] A 2007 HBO film, *Brooklyn Dodgers: The Ghosts of Flatbush*, is a documentary covering the Dodgers history from early days to the beginning of the Los Angeles era.
[src:bill-hill-baseball/brooklyn-superbas] In the film, the story is related that O'Malley was so hated by Brooklyn Dodger fans after the move to California, that it was said: "If you asked a Brooklyn Dodger fan, if you had a gun with only two bullets in it and were in a room with Hitler, Stalin, and O'Malley, who would you shoot?
